				\begin{document}$$Z$$\end{document}Z axes. In the case of the DDKT, RF and MR of angular acceleration and linear accelerations in all axes best distinguished between ataxics and controls [12].

Statistically significant difference between ataxics and controls were identified using hypothesis tests. Normality in the variables was tested using the ShapiroâWilk test. The t-Studentâs test was applied for normally distributed variables. The Wilcoxon rank-sum test or MannâWhitney U test was applied for variables that were not normally distributed. To test for validity, Spearman correlation was used to measure the relationship between objective measurements and clinical scales. The sample size used in this study was determined to detect the minimum effect size of 0.88 with 80% statistical power and significance level (\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
